'''Kevin Peter Pietersen''' [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] (born [[27 June]] [[1980]] in [[Pietermaritzburg]], [[KwaZulu-Natal Province|Natal]], [[South Africa]]) is an English [[cricket]]er. He is an attacking right-handed [[batsman]] and occasional [[off spin]] [[bowler (cricket)|bowler]] who plays for [[Hampshire County Cricket Club]] and is a member of both the [[English cricket team|England]] [[Test cricket|Test match]] and [[One Day International]] teams. 

He made his [[First-class cricket|first-class]] debut for [[KwaZulu Natal cricket team|Natal]] in 1997 before [[International cricketers of South African origin|moving to England]] after voicing his displeasure at the [[racial quota]] system in place in South Africa,<ref name="cricinfo">[http://content-usa.cricinfo.com/england/content/player/19296.html Kevin Pietersen biography], [[Cricinfo]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref> and in order to further his opportunities for playing at international level.  Being born of an English mother gave Pietersen eligibility to play for England, and after serving a qualifying period of four years playing at [[county cricket|county]] level, he was called up almost immediately into the national side. He made his international debut in the One-day International match against [[Zimbabwe national cricket team|Zimbabwe]] in 2004,<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/8/8063/One-Day_International_Matches.html One-day International Matches played by Kevin Pietersen], [[Cricketarchive]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref> and his Test match debut in the [[2005 Ashes series]] against [[Australia national cricket team|Australia]] the following year.<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/8/8063/Test_Matches.html Test Matches played by Kevin Pietersen], Cricketarchive. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref> 
  
Pietersen quickly became the fastest batsman to reach both 1000 and 2000 runs in One-day International cricket,<ref name="fastest to 1000">[http://www.cricinfo.com/db/STATS/ODIS/BATTING/FASTEST_ODI_CAREER_RUNS/ODI_FASTEST_TO_1000_RUNS.html ODIs - Fastest to 1000 Career Runs], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref><ref name="fastest to 2000">Rajesh, S and Gopalakrishna, HR. "[http://content-www.cricinfo.com/wc2007/content/story/291874.html Pietersen breaks a jinx]", Cricinfo, [[2007-04-21]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> and currently has the highest average of any England player to have played more than 20 innings of one-day cricket.<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Records/England/Odis/Career_Batting_by_Average.html Career Batting and Fielding for England in ODIs] Cricketarchive. Retrieved on [[2007-06-03]].</ref> He also has the second-highest run total from his first 25 Tests, behind only the Australian [[Donald Bradman]].<ref name="brenkley">Brenkley, Stephen. "[http://sport.independent.co.uk/cricket/article2586624.ece Second Test: Pietersen plunders before the collapse]", [[The Independent]], [[2007-05-27]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> He became only the third English batsman to top the ICC One-day International rankings, doing so in March 2007.<ref>"[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvaus/content/story/287248.html Pietersen jumps to top of ODI rankings]", Cricinfo, [[2007-03-26]]. Retrieved [[2007-06-06]].</ref>

==Early and personal life==
Born of an [[England|English]] mother and an [[Afrikaner]] father, Penny and Jannie<ref name="cricinfo"/> Pietersen had a strict and well-disciplined childhood, along with his three brothers Tony, Greg and Bryan;<ref>[http://kevin-pietersen.tripod.com/id1.html The Man with the Hair]. Retrieved on [[2007-06-05]].</ref> he learned valuable lessons from this "fantastic" approach to parenting, and said: "Discipline is good. It taught me that I didn't always have to have what I wanted; that what I needed was different from what I wanted."  <ref name="cooke">Cooke, Rachel. "[http://observer.guardian.co.uk/osm/story/0,,1882063,00.html 'I was up at six. I've a party to go to. So what is it you want?']", [[The Observer]], [[2006-10-01]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref>In his autobiography he refers to himself and his brothers getting the cane both at home and at school.  Bryan is currently playing club and second XI cricket in England.<ref>"[http://www.wansteadandwoodfordguardian.co.uk/sport/cricket/display.var.849912.0.pietersen_looks_for_essex_move.php Pietersen looks for Essex move]", Guardian-Series, [[2006-07-27]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-31]].</ref>

Pietersen attended [[Maritzburg College]], [[Pietermaritzburg]], and made his [[first-class cricket]] debut for [[KwaZulu Natal cricket team|Natal]]'s B team in 1997, aged 17, where he was regarded predominantly as an [[off spin]] bowler and a hard-hitting lower-order batsman.<ref name="Brenkley2">Brenkley, Stephen. "[http://sport.independent.co.uk/cricket/article10464.ece Pietersen faces sternest test on home turf]." The Independent, [[2005-02-11]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-29]].</ref><ref name="notts">Borland, Ken. "[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/92818.html Nottinghamshire sign young South African]", Cricinfo, [[2000-10-03]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref> After two seasons, he moved to England for a five-month spell as the overseas player for club side [[Cannock]] CC, and helped them win the [[Birmingham and District Premier League]] in 2000.<ref name="cannock">"[http://www.expressandstar.co.uk/2006/09/06/pietersen-in-cricket-club-row/ Pietersen in cricket club row]", [[Express & Star]], [[2006-09-06]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref> This first spell away from home did not leave him with fond memories for England, in particular "those horrible Black Country accents", living in a single room above a squash court, and working in the club bar.<ref name="cooke"/>  However, he returned to newly-renamed [[KwaZulu Natal cricket team|KwaZulu Natal]] side a better cricketer, a lack of opportunities to bowl having improved his batting.<ref name="cannock"/> 

Pietersen is widely portrayed in the media as having a self-assured personality, described by [[Geoffrey Boycott]] as being "cocky and confident".<ref>Boycott, Geoffrey. "[http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/main.jhtml?xml=/sport/2005/09/13/scboyc13.xml Warne lets the urn slip from his grasp]", [[The Telegraph]], [[2005-12-09]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> England test captain [[Michael Vaughan]] counters this, saying, "KP is not a confident person. He obviously has great belief in his ability but that's not quite the same thing...And I know KP wants to be loved. I try to text him and talk to him as often as I can because I know he is insecure."<ref>McRae, Donald. "[http://sport.guardian.co.uk/cricket/story/0,10069,1594567,00.html Psychology that guides England's man of steel]", The Guardian, [[2005-10-18]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref> He has been noted for his unusual haircuts, with his peroxide blond dyed streak of hair along the middle of his head during the [[2005 Ashes series]] being described as a "dead skunk" look.<ref>William, Richard. "[http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk_news/story/0,,1568634,00.html After 16 years, to England, the Ashes]", The Guardian, [[2005-09-13]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref> During the [[2006-07 Ashes|2006&ndash;07 Ashes]] tour, the Australian team, noted for their efforts to dominate opponents psychologically, dubbed him "The Ego", or "FIGJAM" (Fuck I'm Good, Just Ask Me).<ref>Fraser, Angus. "[http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_20061230/ai_n17091835- Buchanan slates Pietersen for selfish attitude]", The Independent, [[2006-12-30]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref>  Other [[nickname]]s include ''KP'', ''Kelves'' and ''Kapes''.<ref name="cricinfo"/>

Pietersen was rumoured to be dating model [[Caprice Bourret]] who accompanied him to the [[International Cricket Council|ICC]] awards in October 2005,<ref>"[http://www.ecb.co.uk/england/pietersen-scoops-icc-award,6395,EN.html Ashes stars collect ICC Prizes]", [[England and Wales Cricket Board|ecb.co.uk]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref> but he is now married to [[Liberty X]] singer [[Jessica Taylor (Liberty X)|Jessica Taylor]].<ref>Greenstreet, Rosanna. "[http://www.guardian.co.uk/weekend/story/0,,1861841,00.html Q&A]", The Guardian, [[2006-09-02]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref> The couple married on 29 December 2007 at the Manor House Hotel in Wiltshire, with former England team-mate [[Darren Gough]] acting as best man.<ref>Baker, Andrew. "[http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/main.jhtml?xml=/sport/2007/04/18/scbake18.xml Dancing to Gough's tune]", The Telegraph, [[2007-04-18]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref>

==Domestic career==
He impressed members of [[Nasser Hussain]]'s England side when playing for [[KwaZulu Natal cricket team|KwaZulu Natal]] in 1999; he took four top-order wickets and, despite batting at number nine, scored 61 [[not out]] from 57 balls, hitting four sixes.<ref>[http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1999-2000/ENG_IN_RSA/SCORECARDS/ENG_KZN_03-06DEC1999.html KwaZulu-Natal v England XI 3-6 December 1999], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> Hussain then recommended that Pietersen secure a contract with an English county side.<ref>Compton, Patrick. "[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/78799.html Hussain impressed with Pieterson]", Cricinfo, [[1999-12-06]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref>

Despite the praise from the England side, Pietersen was dropped from the Natal first team. Pietersen felt that this was due to the country's [[racial quota]] system, in which provincial sides were required to have at least four non-white players.<ref name="cricinfo"/><ref name="storm">"[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/270556.html Pietersen in the eye of a storm]", Cricinfo, [[2006-12-01]]. Retrieved on [[2007-06-04]].</ref><ref>McRae, Donald. "[http://sport.guardian.co.uk/ashes2005/story/0,15993,1519454,00.html The heartache that honed a hardcore hitter]", The Guardian, [[2005-07-02]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref> Pietersen's view was that players should be judged on merit, and described it as "heartbreaking" when he was left out of the side, although he later reflected "it turned out it was the best thing that could have happened".<ref>"[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/258181.html Racial quotas led Pietersen to leave South Africa]", Cricinfo, [[2006-08-30]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref> Pietersen has since firmly criticised the quota system,<ref>"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/6198644.stm SA hit back at Pietersen comments]", [[BBC Sport]], [[2006-12-01]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref> which he feels forced him out of the country of his birth. He has also criticised [[Graeme Smith]], who became captain of the South African side in 2003, calling him "an absolute muppet, childish and strange" and that his behaviour "leaves a lot to be desired".<ref>"[http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/sport/article-23376544-details/Pietersen%20could%20face%20four-Test%20ban/article.do Pietersen could face four-test ban]", thisislondon.co.uk, [[2006-11-30]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref> Smith opposed this, saying, "I'm patriotic about my country, and that's why I don't like Kevin Pietersen. The only reason that Kevin and I have never had a relationship is because he slated South Africa".<ref>"[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/258408.html Graeme Smith slams Pietersen]", Cricinfo, [[2006-09-02]]. Retrieved on [[2007-06-05]].</ref> His outspoken views published in his autobiography, ''Crossing the Boundary'', in September 2006, and in an interview for South African magazine ''[[GQ (magazine)|GQ]]'', led to unsuccessful calls for an [[International Cricket Council|ICC]] investigation regarding bringing the game into disrepute.<ref>Pietersen, Kevin (2006). ''Crossing the Boundary: The Early Years in my Cricketing Life''. Ebury Press. ISBN 0091912059.</ref><ref name="storm"/>

In 2000, [[Nottinghamshire County Cricket Club|Nottinghamshire]] coach [[Clive Rice]], who had seen Pietersen play in 1997 in South Africa at a schools week, heard that Pietersen was playing club cricket in Birmingham and offered him a three-year contract to play for the county.<ref name="notts"/>  His maiden first-class century came on his Nottinghamshire debut against [[Loughborough UCCE]].<ref name="kpzone">Collins, Sam. "[http://www.cricinfo.com/kevinpietersenzone/timeline.html Rise of a star]", Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2005-05-28]].</ref> In his first season he made 1,275 runs with an impressive [[batting average]] of 57.95,<ref name="Booth">Booth, Lawrence. "[http://content-www.cricinfo.com/wisdencricketer/content/story/134539.html Southern comfort]", [[The Wisden Cricketer]], April 2004. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref> including 218 not out in an unbroken sixth-wicket stand of 352 with [[John Morris (cricketer)|John Morris]] at [[Derby]] in July, after having been out [[Leg before wicket|lbw]] for a [[duck (cricket)|duck]] in the first innings.<ref>"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/counties/1465474.stm Pietersen enjoys run feast]", BBC Sport, [[2001-07-30]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref> These performances led to praise in the ''[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]'': "If he can maintain his first season's form, the name of Pietersen should be pencilled in for future Test squads."<ref name="Booth"/> This form did indeed continue into the following year: he made another unbeaten double-century, against [[Middlesex County Cricket Club|Middlesex]], taking part in a partnership of 316 for the fourth wicket with [[Darren Bicknell]].<ref>[http://sl.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/2002/ENG_LOCAL/CC2/SCORECARDS/14-19AUG2002/NOTTS_MIDDX_CC2_14-17AUG2002.html  Nottinghamshire v Middlesex, 14-16 August 2002], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref> This period proved to be a [[purple prose|purple patch]] for the batsman, scoring four consecutive centuries (254 not out, 122, 147 and 116) in one week in August.<ref>"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/counties/2210644.stm Pietersen piles on the runs]", BBC Sport, [[2002-08-22]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref> 

In 2003, Pietersen scored 1,546 [[first-class cricket|first-class]] runs, and 764 runs in [[limited overs cricket]].<ref name="kpzone"/><ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/8/8063/a_Batting_by_Season.html List A Batting and Fielding in Each Season by Kevin Pietersen], Cricketarchive. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref> He was selected for the 2003&ndash;04 [[ECB National Academy]] tour of India, and had a successful tour scoring 523 runs including three centuries in his six first-class innings to record an average of 104.60,<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/8/8063/f_Batting_by_Season.html First-class Batting and Fielding in Each Season by Kevin Pietersen], Cricketarchive. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref>  and making 131 in a one-day match against India A in [[Bangalore]].<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/79/79041.html India A v England A in 2003/4], Cricketarchive, [[2004-02-10]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref>

After Nottinghamshire were relegated in 2003, Pietersen requested a release from his contract, saying "I haven't been happy for a while....The pitch at [[Trent Bridge]] has been one of my problems... I could have done so much better if the wicket had been good."<ref>"[http://content-www.cricinfo.com/wisdencricketer/content/story/132889.html Pietersen confirms he wants to quit Notts]", Cricinfo, [[2003-10-15]]. Retrieved on [[2007-06-05]].</ref> This led to a public row with club captain [[Jason Gallian]], where Gallian allegedly threw Pietersen's kit off the [[Trent Bridge]] balcony and broke his bat:
<blockquote>During the game I told the captain that I was not happy and that I wanted to leave. After the game we spoke in the dressing room and then I went to have dinner. I got a call saying the captain had trashed my equipment. I was told the captain had said, 'if he does not want to play for Notts he can f*** off.' I have not spoken to Gallian since, nor have I received an apology.<ref>"[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/136698.html Pietersen seeks release from Nottinghamshire]", Cricinfo, [[2004-01-16]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref></blockquote> Pietersen was made to honour the last year of his contract at Nottinghamshire, but "didn't enjoy it at all".<ref>John, Emma. "[http://content-www.cricinfo.com/wisdencricketer/content/story/146400.html The only lane is the fast lane]", Cricinfo, [[2005-03-23]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref> In October 2004, he joined [[Hampshire County Cricket Club|Hampshire]] under the captaincy of [[Shane Warne]].<ref>"[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/142765.html Pietersen signs for Hampshire], Cricinfo, [[2004-10-26]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref>

After becoming a regular in the international side, Pietersen rarely gets an opportunity to play domestic cricket. Having an England "central contract" means that Pietersen is only released to play for Hampshire at the discretion of the national coach. After being left out of the national side to face [[Bangladesh national cricket team|Bangladesh]] in May 2005, Pietersen had several good innings in the four-day county championship, including two centuries.<ref>"[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/209752.html Pietersen posts another reminder]", Cricinfo, [[2005-05-21]]. Retrieved on [[2007-06-03]].</ref> He only played twice for the county in 2006, and has played once so far in 2007, with an unbeaten 66 against [[Ireland cricket team|Ireland]].<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/107/107510.html Hampshire v Ireland], Cricketarchive, [[2007-05-07]]. Retrieved on [[2007-06-03]].</ref>

==International career==
====Success in South Africa====
{{See also|English cricket team in Zimbabwe in 2004-05|English cricket team in South Africa in 2004-05}}
The tour of [[Zimbabwe]] caused several players to voice their concerns about the [[Robert Mugabe]] regime, the security issues in  the country and the standard of the [[Zimbabwe cricket team|Zimbabwean]] side.<ref>"[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/zimbabwe/content/story/143154.html England agree to five-match series in Zimbabwe]", Cricinfo, [[2004-09-09]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-30]].</ref> [[Steve Harmison]] was the first to boycott the tour for "political and sporting reasons",<ref>"[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvwi/content/story/143416.html Harmison opts out of Zimbabwe tour]", Cricinfo, [[2004-09-19]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-30]].</ref> and all-rounder [[Andrew Flintoff]] was reported to be considering taking a moral stand himself. The England Chairman of Selectors [[David Graveney]] denied that the selectors would leave out players unhappy with touring Zimbabwe and would put their absences down to injury.<ref>"[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvwi/content/story/143599.html Full-strength side will tour Zimbabwe]", Cricinfo, [[2004-09-26]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-30]].</ref> Flintoff was, however, "rested" and Pietersen rushed into the squad "at the earliest opportunity".<ref>"[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvwi/content/story/143632.html Flintoff and Trescothick stay at home]", Cricinfo, [[2004-09-28]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-30]].</ref> In the five match ODI series, Pietersen batted in three innings which included a score of 77 not out; he finished the series with an average of 104.00 as England won the series 4&ndash;0.

Pietersen was upset not to be initially in the squad to tour [[South Africa]].<ref>"[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/142649.html Pietersen hits out at non-selection]", Cricinfo, [[2004-10-20]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-30]].</ref> With Flintoff withdrawing due to injury,<ref>"[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvwi/content/story/145551.html Flintoff surgery is confirmed]", Cricinfo, [[2005-01-25]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-30]].</ref> Pietersen was recalled to the squad,<ref>"[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/145268.html Pietersen added to England's one-day squad]", Cricinfo, [[2005-01-14]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-29]].</ref> and cemented his place in the first team with 97 off 84 balls in the warm-up match against South Africa A, in the face of a hostile crowd.<ref>Majendie, Matt. "[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/4215057.stm Pietersen enters South Africa cauldron]", BBC Sport, [[2005-01-28]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> Throughout the tour, Pietersen was subjected to a barrage of abuse from the South African crowd, who regarded him somewhat like a [[traitor]].<ref name="Brenkley2"/> He said:
<blockquote>I knew I was going to cop a lot of stick but it will be like water off a duck's back...I expected stick at the start of the innings, and I'm sure it will carry on through the whole series. But I just sat back and laughed at the opposition, with their swearing and 'traitor' remarks... some of them can hardly speak English. My affiliation is with England. In fact, I'm starting to speak too much like [[Darren Gough]]... In fact, I'm going to get one of Gough's tattoos with three lions and my number underneath...No one can say I'm not English.<ref>"[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/145622.html Pietersen says abuse is 'water off a duck's back']", Cricinfo, [[2005-01-28]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref> 
</blockquote>

Pietersen scored a 96-ball 108 not out in the [[The result in cricket#tie|tied]] second [[One Day International|ODI]] at [[Bloemfontein]], after which the crowd turned their backs on him as he returned to the pavilion.<ref>Miller, Andrew. "[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/144265.html It's a tie after a last-ball thriller]", Cricinfo, [[2005-02-02]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]]</ref> This score set his ODI average at an incredible record 234.00.<ref>[http://www.sportstats.com.au/blognov04tojun05.html Z-scoreâ€™s Cricket Stats Blog Archive, Nov 2004 to Jun 2005]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref><ref>[http://www.howstat.com/cricket/Statistics/Players/PlayerProgressSummary_ODI.asp?PlayerID=3238 HowStat! ODI Kevin Pietersen: Batting - Progressive Average and Aggregate], HowStat. Retrieved [[2007-05-28]].</ref> He made 75 at [[Cape Town]],<ref>Thompson, Jenny. "[http://content-www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/144350.html South Africa trounce England by 108 runs]", Cricinfo, [[2005-02-06]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]]</ref> then at [[East London, South Africa|East London]] Pietersen made an unbeaten 100 from only 69 balls, the fastest century by an England player in a one-day match,<ref name="Thompson fastest century">Thompson, Jenny. "[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/144479.html Pietersen century all in vain]", Cricinfo, [[2005-02-09]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-26]].</ref> although England still lost by eight runs. In the final game at [[Centurion Park]], Pietersen came to the wicket at 32/3 and scored 116, but again could not prevent a defeat. Pietersen ended the series, which England lost 4&ndash;1, with 454 runs in five innings, and the Player of the Series award.<ref>"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/4260173.stm England sign off with fourth loss]", BBC Sport, [[2005-02-13]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref><ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/RSA/2004-05_RSA_England_in_South_Africa_2004-05.html England in South Africa 2004/05], Cricketarchive. Retrieved on [[28 May]], [[2007]].</ref> By the end of the series, the South African crowds had generally replaced hostility with respect for Pietersen, his final century being awarded a standing ovation.<ref>Fraser, Angus. "[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_20050802/ai_n14827270 Cricket: Giles' amazing show of insecurity invites the Australians]", The Independent, [[2005-08-02]]. Retrieved on [[2007-02-27]].</ref>

====Mixed success in Ashes build-up====
{{See also|Bangladeshi cricket team in England in 2005|Australian cricket team in England in 2005}}
Despite press speculation, Pietersen was not picked for the [[Test cricket|Tests]] against [[Bangladeshi cricket team|Bangladesh]]&mdash;his early season form being dogged by a foot injury<ref>"[http://www.ecb.co.uk/domestic/england-star-shrugs-off-foot-injury,3706,EN.html Pietersen set to make his debut]", [[England and Wales Cricket Board|ecb.co.uk]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref><ref>"[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvban/content/story/209327.html No room for Pietersen in England squad]", Cricinfo, [[2005-05-15]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref>&mdash;but with his county form improving, he was selected for the [[Twenty20]] match against [[Australian cricket team|Australia]] at [[Southampton]], making 34 from 18 balls and taking three catches as England won by 100 runs.<ref>[http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2005/AUS_IN_ENG/SCORECARDS/AUS_ENG_TWENTY-20-I_13JUN2005.html England v Australia 20:20, 13 June 2005], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]]</ref> 

In the triangular ODI series against Australia and Bangladesh, Pietersen did not get to bat in the first match at [[The Oval]] as England won by 10 wickets, but scored 91 off 65 balls in the match in [[Bristol]] against Australia.<ref>[http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2005/OD_TOURNEYS/NWS/SCORECARDS/AUS_ENG_NWS_ODI3_19JUN2005.html England v Australia ODI, 19 June 2005], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> In the remainder of the triangular series, Pietersen scored quickly, although without other half-centuries. He finished the seven-match series with a total of 278 runs at an average of 46.33.<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/ENG/National_Westminster_Bank_Series_2005/England_Batting.html Batting and Fielding for England in National Westminster Bank Series 2005], Cricketarchive. Retrieved on [[2007-06-05]].</ref> 

Pietersen's performances sparked speculation over whether he would be brought into the Test side for [[The Ashes]] later in the summer.  A [[BBC]] poll of 10 respected cricketers resulted in a minor preference for playing Pietersen and [[Ian Bell (cricketer)|Ian Bell]] in the [[Batsman (cricket)#Middle order|middle order]], with [[Graham Thorpe]] missing out.<ref>"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/4110676.stm Three into two won't go]", BBC Sport, [[2005-06-20]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref>

Later in July, Pietersen played in all three matches of the (ODI) NatWest Challenge against Australia. In the final match he was the top scorer for England with 74 runs, however he was forced off the field in the third over of Australia's reply with a groin injury.<ref>McGlashan, Andrew. "[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvaus/content/story/213353.html Australia show their finest timing]", Cricinfo, [[2005-06-12]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref>

====2005 Ashes triumph====
[[Image:Kevin Pieterson at Lords Final.jpg|thumb|right|Pietersen warming up in the nets at [[Lord's Cricket Ground|Lord's]] in September 2005.]]
{{See also|2005 Ashes series}}
Speculation over when Pietersen would play for the Test team was ended in July with the announcement by the England chairman of selectors, [[David Graveney]], that Pietersen had been selected ahead of [[Graham Thorpe]].<ref>"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/4676287.stm England drop Thorpe for Pietersen]", BBC Sport, [[2005-07-14]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref>  He made his debut in the first Ashes Test at [[Lord's Cricket Ground|Lord's]], becoming the 626 player to play for the national side.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/player/caps.html?country=1;class=1 England Caps], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-06-06]].</ref> Pietersen scored 57 and 64 not out as England collapsed to a heavy defeat, becoming only the fourth player to top score in both innings on debut for England, the eighth England player to score a half-century in each innings on his debut, and the third cricketer to do so at Lord's.<ref name="Lynch">Lynch, Steven. "[http://content-www.cricinfo.com/columns/content/story/214802.html Pietersen's double debut double]", Cricinfo, [[2005-08-01]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> In the second Test at Edgbaston he scored 71 in the first innings and 20 in the second, with England narrowly winning by 2 runs.<ref>[http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2005/AUS_IN_ENG/SCORECARDS/AUS_ENG_T2_04-08AUG2005.html England v Australia Second Test, 4-7 August 2005], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> 

In the drawn third Test, Pietersen struggled with 21 and 0, then scored 45 and 23 in the fourth as England went 2-1 up.<ref>[http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2005/AUS_IN_ENG/SCORECARDS/AUS_ENG_T3_11-15AUG2005.html England v Australia Third Test, 11-15 August 2005], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref><ref>[http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2005/AUS_IN_ENG/SCORECARDS/AUS_ENG_T4_25-29AUG2005.html England v Australia Fourth Test, 25-28 August 2005], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> Under pressure to post a large score in the final Test at [[The Oval]], Pietersen did not contribute significantly in the first innings with 14.  In the second innings, Pietersen was dropped twice before reaching double figures, but went on to score his maiden Test century with 158, drawing the match and securing the series for England.<ref name="kpzone"/><ref>Grunill, Paul. "[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/4238344.stm Oval hero Pietersen]", BBC Sport, [[2005-09-12]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> His innings included seven sixes, a record for an English player in an Ashes innings.<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/db/STATS/TESTS/BATTING/TRIVIA/BAT_MOST_SIXES_TEST.html Tests - Most Sixes in an Innings], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> Pietersen was named [[Man of the Match]] for his efforts,<ref>[http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2005/AUS_IN_ENG/SCORECARDS/AUS_ENG_T5_08-12SEP2005.html England v Australia Fifth Test, 8-12 September 2005], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> and finished the series as top scorer, with 473 runs over the five Tests, an average of 52.55.<ref>[http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2005/AUS_IN_ENG/STATS/AUS_IN_ENG_JUN-SEP2005_TEST_AVS.html Australia in England, 2005 Test Series Averages], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> However, he had a less successful series in the field, dropping six catches in the five Tests, a point he made wryly when questioned about the Australians dropping him three times on the final day.<ref>[http://content-www.cricinfo.com/quote/content/story/231681.html The best quotes of 2005], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> Pietersen was given an [[England and Wales Cricket Board|ECB]] "central contract" to reflect his place in the national side.<ref>"[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/214969.html Pietersen awarded central contract]", Cricinfo, [[2005-08-03]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]]</ref>

====Less rewarding winter tour====
{{See also|English cricket team in Pakistan in 2005-06|English cricket team in India in 2005-06}}
Pietersen had a less successful time in the three Test matches against [[Pakistan national cricket team|Pakistan]], which England lost 2&ndash;0. He made little impact in the first and third Tests, his highest score being 34.<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2005-06/ENG_IN_PAK/SCORECARDS/ENG_PAK_T1_12-16NOV2005.html Pakistan v England First Test, 12-16 November 2005], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-05-29]].</ref><ref>[http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2005-06/ENG_IN_PAK/SCORECARDS/ENG_PAK_T3_29NOV-03DEC2005.html Pakistan v England Third Test, 29 November-03 December, 2005], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-05-30]].</ref> He fared better in the second, however, making his second Test century in the first innings.<ref>"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/4457390.stm Pietersen & Bell hit England tons]", BBC Sport, [[2005-11-22]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> He was also performing well in the one-day series with two explosive innings of 56 from 39 balls to help England win the first ODI, and 28 from 27 balls in the second.<ref>[http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2005-06/ENG_IN_PAK/SCORECARDS/ENG_PAK_ODI1_10DEC2005.html Pakistan v England First ODI, 10 December, 2005], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-05-29]].</ref><ref>[http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2005-06/ENG_IN_PAK/SCORECARDS/ENG_PAK_ODI2_12DEC2005.html Pakistan v England Second ODI, 12 December, 2005], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-05-30]].</ref> The quick-scoring innings in the second ODI was to be Pietersen's last on the tour. A rib injury sustained in the first ODI proved too painful throughout the second, and Pietersen returned to England to recover fully for the tour of India.<ref>"[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakveng/content/story/229473.html Pietersen forced home by rib injury]", Cricinfo, [[2005-12-13]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-30]].</ref> 

In March 2006, Pietersen played in the three Tests against [[India national cricket team|India]], which England drew 1&ndash;1. His 87 in the second innings of the first match came during England's acceleration period, helping push the required target over 300.<ref>[http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2005-06/ENG_IN_IND/SCORECARDS/ENG_IND_T1_01-05MAR2006_BBB-COMMS.html India v England, First Test, 01-05 March, 2005 Ball-by-ball commentary], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-05-30]].</ref> England then declared overnight, and India successfully batted out the final day to secure a draw. This half-century was followed by another in the first innings of the second Test. The second innings was not so good, facing just 13 balls before being given out [[caught behind]] off a [[Harbhajan Singh]] delivery.  The unhappy Pietersen was later fined 30 percent of his match fee for shaking his head and showing signs of dissent.<ref name="dissent">"[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/240601.html Pietersen fined for dissent]", Cricinfo, [[2006-03-13]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> "Replays demonstrated that the ball that had dismissed him had brushed his forearm, not his glove, before ballooning up into the hands of [[Rahul Dravid]] at slip. But umpire [[Darrell Hair]] gave him out for 4 as England collapsed on the fourth afternoon."<ref name="dissent"/> Pietersen posted scores of 39 and 7 in the final Test, a match England won comfortably after a dismal 100 all out in India's second visit to the crease.<ref>[http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2005-06/ENG_IN_IND/SCORECARDS/ENG_IND_T3_18-22MAR2006.html India v England, Third Test, 18-22 March, 2006], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-05-30]].</ref>

In the one-day series, which England lost 5&ndash;1, he was top scorer for England in four out of the five matches he played, and had the highest average of any player with 58.20.<ref>[http://usa.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2005-06/ENG_IN_IND/STATS/ENG_IN_IND_FEB-APR2006_ODI_AVS.html England in India, 2005-06 One-day Series Averages], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-05-29]].</ref> His 71 in the second ODI took him past 1,000 ODI runs, equalling [[Viv Richards]]' record of 21 innings to reach this total.<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/db/STATS/ODIS/BATTING/FASTEST_ODI_CAREER_RUNS/ODI_FASTEST_TO_1000_RUNS.html ODIs - Fastest to 1000 Career Runs], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref>

====Sri Lanka and Pakistan in England, 2006====
{{See also|Sri Lankan cricket team in England in 2006|Pakistani cricket team in England in 2006}}
[[Image:Kevin pietersen bowl.jpg|right|thumb|'''Pietersen bowls [[off-spin]]''' in the [[Adelaide Oval]] nets in November 2006.]]
In May 2006, Pietersen matched his highest Test score of 158 in the first match against [[Sri Lanka national cricket team|Sri Lanka]],<ref>McGlashan, Andrew. "[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/246911.html Mahmood and Pietersen leave Sri Lanka in tatters]", Cricinfo, [[2006-05-12]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> and followed it with 142 in the second Test.<ref>McGlashan, Andrew. "[http://content-www.cricinfo.com/engvsl/content/current/story/248428.html Bowlers build on Pietersen's stunning century]", Cricinfo, [[2006-05-26]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> This took him passed the milestone of 1,000 Test runs, in his 12th Test match, and he became the first batsman since [[Graham Gooch]] in 1990 to score a century in three successive Test innings on English soil.<ref>Kumar, Manish. "[http://www.cricketzone.com/news/news_columns/2007-03-08-98.html Will England rise from the Ashes for the World Cup?]", cricketzone.com, [[2007-03-08]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> This performance moved Pietersen into the top ten of the [[ICC cricket ratings]], as he was named the England (Test Match) Player of the Series.<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/ENG/2006_ENG_Sri_Lanka_in_England_2006.html Sri Lanka in England 2006], Cricketarchive. Retrieved [[28 May]], [[2007]].</ref><ref>"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/5026308.stm Pietersen moves into Test top 10]", BBC Sport, [[2006-05-29]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref>
On the first day of the third Test against Pakistan, Pietersen reached his fifth Test century with an overnight score of 104. Although Pietersen retired hurt shortly after reaching three figures, due to cramp, he returned to the crease the next morning and went on to top score in England's first innings total of 515 with 135 runs from 169 balls.<ref>McGlashan, Andrew. "[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvpak/content/story/255643.html Yousuf leads Pakistan reply after Bell's third ton]", Cricinfo, [[2006-08-05]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref>
 
Pietersen bowled his first delivery in Test match cricket on [[June 4]], against Sri Lanka.<ref>[http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/engvsl/engine/match/225266.html England v Sri Lanka Third Test, 2-5 June 2006], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref> His first Test wicket came against [[Pakistan national cricket team|Pakistan]] later in the summer when [[Kamran Akmal]] got a thin edge through to [[Geraint Jones]].<ref>McGlashan, Andrew. "[http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/engvpak/content/story/253539.html Pakistan ride on Yousuf special]", Cricinfo, [[2006-07-15]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref>

Later in June, Pietersen scored 17 in the [[Twenty20]] International as England lost by 2 runs to Sri Lanka.<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/85/85632.html England v Sri Lanka, Twenty20], Cricketarchive, [[2006-06-15]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref> The twenty [[over (cricket)|over]] match against Pakistan was no better, Pietersen being [[bowled]] by [[Mohammad Asif]] for a [[duck (cricket)|golden duck]] as Pakistan helped themselves to a five-wicket victory.<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/86/86003.html Pakistan v England, Twenty20], Cricketarchive, [[2006-08-28]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref>

====England in Australia, 2006&ndash;7====
{{See also|2006-07 Ashes series|English cricket team in Australia in 2006-07}}
In the much anticipated Ashes series in Australia, Pietersen was widely judged to be England's best player, scoring 490 runs in five matches and averaging over 50. He started well with a defiant 92 in the first Test despite England losing by 277 runs,<ref>"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/6185580.stm Australia v England - 1st Test]", BBC Sport, [[2006-11-27]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> and then backed up his good form with a century in the second Test in [[Adelaide]],
sharing a 310-run partnership for the fourth wicket with Paul Collingwood. When he was eventually run out, his first reaction was to "giggle" because it was the third time he had scored exactly 158 runs (at that point, his highest Test score).<ref>Miller, Andrew. "[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ausveng/content/story/270774.html Pietersen and Collingwood share the limelight]", Cricinfo, [[2006-12-02]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> However, even Pietersen seemed disheartened by the end of the series, which England lost 5&ndash;0.<ref>Miller, Andrew. "[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/275400.html Pietersen the best of a poor bunch]", Cricinfo, [[2007-01-06]]. Retrieved on [[2007-01-12]].</ref>

In the Twenty20 match, Pietersen was run out on 11, as England lost the match by 77 runs.<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/98/98972.html Australia v England, Twenty20]. Cricketarchive, [[2007-01-09]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref>  For a powerful hitter, Pietersen has not posted a large score in the specialised twenty-over format, averaging 15.50.<ref name="cricinfo"/> In the first One-day International of the 2006&ndash;07 [[Commonwealth Bank Series]], on [[12 January]] at the [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]], Pietersen was injured when a ball bowled by [[Glenn McGrath]] hit him on the ribs. Despite continuing his innings in some discomfort, making 82, [[X-ray]]s revealed a fracture and Pietersen was forced to miss the rest of the series.<ref>Coverdale, Brydon. "[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/cbs/content/current/story/276237.html Pietersen out of tour with fractured rib]", Cricinfo, [[2007-01-12]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref>

====Career in 2007====
{{See also|2007 Cricket World Cup|West Indian cricket team in England in 2007|Indian cricket team in England in 2007}}
In  the [[2007 Cricket World Cup]], Pietersen crafted 104 runs off 122 balls against Australia in the [[2007 Cricket World Cup Super Eight stage|Super Eight]] stage of the tournament. It was the first World Cup century by an Englishman since 1996, and the first ever against Australia.<ref>Rajesh, S and Gopalakrishna, HR. "[http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/wc2007/content/current/story/289672.html How Tait and Hogg turned it around]", Cricinfo, [[2007-04-08]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> He made three half-centuries, scoring 60 runs from 92 balls against [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand]],<ref>[http://content-www.cricinfo.com/wc2007/engine/match/247463.html England v New Zealand, 16 March 2007], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> 56 runs from 72 balls against [[Kenya national cricket team|Kenya]],<ref>[http://content-sl.cricinfo.com/wc2007/engine/match/247479.html England v Kenya, 24 March 2007], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> and 58 runs from 80 balls against [[Sri Lanka national cricket team|Sri Lanka]].<ref>[http://content-www.cricinfo.com/stlucia/engine/match/247489.html England v Sri Lanka, 4 April 2007], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> His efforts in the World Cup helped him achieve the status of [[ICC]] number-one ranked batsman in the world for ODIs;<ref>"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/6494577.stm Pietersen top of world rankings]", BBC Sport, [[2007-03-26]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> however, England did not reach the semi-finals.  In England's final match of the World Cup against the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]], Pietersen made 100 from 91 balls, and effected the run-out of retiring captain [[Brian Lara]].<ref>Lillywhite, Jamie. "[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/6576083.stm West Indies v England]", BBC Sport, [[2007-04-21]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> This century took him past 2000 ODI runs, in doing so equalling the record 51 matches set by [[Zaheer Abbas]].<ref name="fastest to 2000"/> He finished the tournament with 444 runs, at an average of 55.5, and was described as shining in the England team "like a 100 watt bulb in a room full of candles".<ref>Goughy, Kev. "[http://www.cricketweb.net/article.php?CategoryIDAuto=4&NewsIDAuto=3885 Team of the 2007 World Cup]", cricketweb.net, [[2007-05-15]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref>

Having scored a century in the first Test against the West Indies at [[Lord's cricket ground|Lord's]],<ref>[http://content-www.cricinfo.com/engvwi/engine/current/match/258459.html England v West Indies First Test, 17-21 May 2007], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]]</ref> Pietersen posted his highest score of 226 in the second Test at [[Headingley Stadium|Headingley]], surpassing his previous best of 158 which he had achieved three times.<ref>"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/6695535.stm Test-best score thrills Pietersen]", BBC Sport, [[2007-05-26]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> With this score, Pietersen moved ahead of [[Everton Weekes]] and [[Viv Richards]] to be the batsman with the second-highest run-total out of his first 25 Tests (behind [[Don Bradman]]).<ref name="brenkley"/> It is also the highest Test score for England since [[Graham Gooch]] scored 333 against [[India cricket team|India]] in 1990.<ref>Mitchell, Kevin. "[http://sport.guardian.co.uk/cricket/story/0,,2089157,00.html?gusrc=rss&feed=7 Peerless Pietersen sets up drubbing]". The Guardian, [[27 May]], [[2007]]. Retrieved on [[28 May]], [[2007]].</ref> This innings subjected the West Indies to an innings and 283 runs defeat, their largest against any team. Pietersen, the Man of the Match, said, "I believe the recipe for success is hard work. I've been criticised for throwing my wicket away, and I tried to make it count here".<ref> "[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvwi/engine/current/match/258460.html?innings=3;view=commentary Commentary: England v West Indies at Leeds, May 25-28, 2007]". Cricinfo, [[2007-05-28]]. Retrieved on [[2007-06-06]].</ref>

In the third Test at [[Old Trafford Cricket Ground|Old Trafford]], scoring 68 in the second innings, Pietersen lost his wicket in a bizarre dismissal when West Indian all-rounder [[Dwayne Bravo]] delivered a [[bouncer (cricket)|bouncer]] which knocked Pietersen's helmet off his head and onto his stumps.  He is only the fourth batsman in Test cricket to be dismissed "[[hit wicket]]" as a result of headgear falling onto the stumps.<ref>Brett, Oliver. "[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/6737017.stm West Indies v England]", BBC Sport, [[2007-06-09]]. Retrieved on [[2007-06-10]].</ref> This score took him past the 8500 first-class runs mark, and 2,500 runs in Test cricket.<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/103/103087/103087_bbb.html England v West Indies 3rd Test match], [[2007-06-11]], Cricketarchive. Retrieved on [[2007-06-11]].</ref>

In contrast, Pietersen's batting was poor in the following single innings matches; he scored a total of 77 runs in five matches (two Twenty20 and three ODI), recording a second-ball duck in the final ODI.<ref>[http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/103/103096.html England v West Indies 3rd ODI], [[2007-07-07]], [[Cricketarchive]]. Retrieved on [[2007-07-07]].</ref> He subsequently fell to second in the official One-day International batting rankings, behind [[Ricky Ponting]].<ref>"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/6121940.stm Pietersen relinquishes top place]", [[2007-07-08]], [[BBC Sport]]. Retrieved on [[2007-07-09]].</ref> Pietersen himself has commented that his lack of recent form is a result of "fatigue", and has reiterated his calls for a less "hectic" match schedule.<ref name=fatigue>"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/6294522.stm Pietersen blames fatigue for form]", [[BBC Sport]]. Retrieved on [[2007-07-12]].</ref>

Pietersen found some form in the first Test against [[India national cricket team|India]], with a magnificent 134 in the second innings to set up a potential England victory. Pietersen described this as his best century, in very testing conditions.<ref>Miller, Andrew "[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ci/content/current/story/303195.html 'I'd probably rate that as No. 1']", [[2007-07-22]], [[Cricinfo]]. Retrieved on [[2007-07-23]].</ref> After two low scores in the second Test, Pietersen scored his 10th Test Century in the third and final Test at the Oval, helping England to draw the game with 101.<ref>[http://content-www.cricinfo.com/engvind/engine/match/258470.html England v India Third Test, 9-13 August 2007], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-08-15]]</ref>

Pietersen was also picked for and played in the Twenty20 Championship in South Africa. In England's first game against Zimbabwe on [[September 13]], Pietersen hit 79 runs off 37 balls including four sixes and seven fours in an English total of 188-9. England won the match by 50 runs, however this was to be Pietersens only significant contribution in the competition.{{Fact|date=December 2007}}

===Sri Lanka 2007&ndash;8===

Pietersen travelled to [[Sri Lanka]] with England's ODI squad in September 2007. He scored 50 in England's warm up game against the Sri Lankan Cricket XI,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2007/9/14133/html/scorecard.stm ''Tour Match: Sri Lanka Cricket XI v England''] [[BBC News]] retrieved [[November 22]] [[2007]]</ref> however followed this with scores of one,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2007/10/14134/html/scorecard.stm ''ODI vs. Sri Lanka, 1st Match''] [[BBC News]] retrieved [[November 22]] [[2007]]</ref> twelve,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2007/10/14135/html/scorecard.stm ''ODI vs. Sri Lanka, 2nd Match''] [[BBC News]] retrieved [[November 22]] [[2007]]</ref> and eight.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2007/10/14136/html/scorecard.stm ''ODI vs. Sri Lanka, 3rd Match''] [[BBC News]] retrieved [[November 22]] [[2007]]</ref> He then found form with 63 not out from 75 deliveries <ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2007/10/14137/html/scorecard.stm ''ODI vs. Sri Lanka, 4th Match''] [[BBC News]] retrieved [[November 22]] [[2007]]</ref> to clinch a historic series win for England, the first in the country since the 1980s. He went on to score 28 in the final match which was a consolatory victory for Sri Lanka.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2007/10/14138/html/scorecard.stm ''ODI vs. Sri Lanka, 5th Match''] [[BBC News]] retrieved [[November 22]] [[2007]]</ref> In the first test that followed in November, he was the only batsman not to make double figures in a drawn warm up game against the Board President's XI, being caught for four.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7106856.stm ''Cook stars in tame England draw''] [[BBC News]] retrieved [[November 22]] [[2007]]</ref> In the second warm up match against the Sri Lanka Board XI, Pietersen was again out for a low score in the first innings, surviving just three balls and scoring one run. In the second, however, England snatched a "surprise" win, with Pietersen finding form and hitting 59, the highest score of England's innings.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7114383.stm ''England snatch surprise tour win''] [[BBC News]] retrieved [[November 27]] [[2007]]</ref>

During the test series, however, Pietersen suffered a period of fluctuating form. Scoring 31 and 18 in the first test,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2007/12/14141/html/scorecard.stm ''Test Match Series: Sri Lanka v England''] [[BBC News]] retrieved [[December 20]] [[2007]]</ref> he managed only a single in the first innings of the second. While he regained his touch for the second innings, with a match saving 45 not out,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2007/12/14142/html/scorecard.stm ''Test Match Series: Sri Lanka v England''] [[BBC News]] retrieved [[December 20]] [[2007]]</ref> he hit one and 30 in the final test,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/england/latest_scorecard/default.stm ''Sri Lanka v England 3rd Test''] [[BBC News]] retrieved [[December 22]] [[2007]]</ref> passing 3,000 test career runs but averaging only 25.2 across the series, failing to score a half century in a series for the first time in his career,<ref>[[Simon Hughes (cricketer)|Hughes, Simon]] [http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/tms/2007/12/england_series_rankings_1.shtml ''England test series ratings''] [[BBC News]] retrieved [[January 2]] [[2008]]</ref> and having the second lowest average of all the recognised batsmen.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/england/averages/default.stm ''Test Series in Sri Lanka, averages''] [[BBC News]] retrieved [[December 22]] [[2007]]</ref> He equalled the Test cricket record for passing 3000 runs within 3 years of playing for his country, with the distinction that he reached this total 6 months earlier than the other two players to achieve this.{{Fact|date=January 2008}}

===New Zealand 2008===

Pietersen averaged 33 in the five match ODI series in early 2008, a high score of 50 and 165 runs overall failing to save England from a 3:1 defeat.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/averages/default.stm England averages vs. New Zealand, 2008] [[BBC News]] retrieved [[February 24]] [[2008]]</ref> The series was preceded by two warm up matches, where Pietersen scored 48,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2008/2/14978/html/scorecard.stm ''Tour Match: Canterbury v England - February 1, 2008''] [[BBC News]] retrieved [[February 24]] [[2008]]</ref> and 10,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2008/2/14304/html/scorecard.stm ''Tour Match: Canterbury v England - February 2, 2008''] [[BBC News]] retrieved [[February 24]] [[2008]]</ref> and two 20Twenty internationals where he scored 43,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2008/2/14305/html/scorecard.stm ''International Twenty20 Series: New Zealand v England - February 5, 2008] [[BBC News]] retrieved [[February 24]] [[2008]]</ref> and 3,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2008/2/14307/html/scorecard.stm '' 	
International Twenty20 Series: New Zealand v England - February 7, 2008] [[BBC News]] retrieved [[February 24]] [[2008]]</ref> each match resulting in an England win. 

England then played a series of warm up matches before the three test series began, where Pietersen would face New Zealand for the first time in his test career. Pietersen, however, did not play in the first warm up match for the test series, as England featured both wicket keepers [[Tim Ambrose]] and [[Phil Mustard]] in thier batting lineup.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2008/2/14313/html/scorecard.stm ''Tour Match: Invitational XI v England''] [[BBC News]] retrieved [[February 24]] [[2008]]</ref>

==Achievements==
===Awards===
Pietersen gained several awards for his performances in the 2005 season. He was named both the [[International Cricket Council|ICC]] ODI Player of the Year and Emerging Player of the Year in 2005,<ref name="ICC awards">"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/4326586.stm Flintoff shares ICC player award]", BBC Sport, [[2005-10-11]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-27]].</ref> and was one of the five [[Wisden Cricketer of the Year|Wisden Cricketers of the Year]] (alongside team mates [[Simon Jones (cricketer)|Simon Jones]] and [[Matthew Hoggard]]) for his role in the successful [[2005 Ashes series|Ashes series]] against Australia.<ref name="Wisden">"[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/243894.html Flintoff named as the leading player of the year]", Cricinfo, [[2006-04-11]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref> Along with the rest of the England team, he was decorated in the [[Orders, decorations, and medals of the United Kingdom|2006 New Year Honours list]], being awarded the MBE for his role in the successful Ashes series.<ref>"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/4625530.stm Ashes heroes get Palace Honours]", BBC Sport, [[2006-02-09]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-28]].</ref> He also played for the [[ICC World XI]] in the [[ICC Super Series 2005]] against Australia.<ref>[http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2005-06/SUPERS/SUPERS_OCT2005_ICC-XI-SQUAD.html ICC World XI Squads], Cricinfo. Retrieved on [[2007-06-06]].</ref>

===Test match performance===
Test debut: vs [[Australia national cricket team|Australia]], [[Lord's cricket ground|Lord's]], [[July 21]], [[2005]].<ref name="cricinfo"/>
* He has the second highest run-total from his first 25 Tests (behind [[Don Bradman]]).<ref name="brenkley"/>
* Fourth Englishman to top score in both innings of debut Test.<ref name="Lynch"/>
* He is one of only twenty-two players to have a peak ICC batting rating over 900.<ref>[http://www.lgiccrankings.com/test/batting/all-time-ranking.php LG ICC Best-Ever Test Batting Ratings], ICC Cricket Rankings. Retrieved on [[2007-07-23]].</ref>

